The solution was to add a global `omnisharp.json` file in `%USERPROFILE%/.omnisharp/` and enable the editorconfig support there. 
```json
{
  "FormattingOptions": {
    "EnableEditorConfigSupport": true
  }
}
```
More information here: https://github.com/OmniSharp/omnisharp-roslyn/wiki/Configuration-Options

I'm not sure what this means, but I think that the configuration is not properly passed to omnisharp and I dosen't respect the .editorconfig file.

I had a similar problem (omnisharp ignoring my `.editorconfig`) after upgrading neovim and all tools and dependencies to current versions. I dug into it and it looks like there is a difference between the old deprecated config at `lua/lspconfig/configs/omnisharp.lua` and the new `lsp/omnisharp.lua`: The old one has a `flatten()` function that converts the options into command line arguments. The new one doesn't do that. I copied that function into my config, which fixes the issue:

``` lua
local servers = {
  clangd = {},
  omnisharp = {
    cmd = { 'dotnet', vim.fn.stdpath 'data' .. '/mason/packages/omnisharp/libexec/OmniSharp.dll', '--languageserver' },
    settings = {
      FormattingOptions = {
        EnableEditorConfigSupport = true,
      },
      RoslynExtensionsOptions = {
        -- ...
      },
    },
  },

  lua_ls = {
    settings = {
      -- ...
    },
  },
}

-- OmniSharp reads settings from cmd-line args, not LSP workspace/configuration.
-- The old nvim-lspconfig on_new_config hook did this, but the new lsp/*.lua
-- configs dropped it. See: lspconfig/configs/omnisharp.lua (deprecated) vs
-- lsp/omnisharp.lua (current). Flatten settings into cmd args ourselves.
if servers.omnisharp and servers.omnisharp.settings then
  local function flatten(tbl)
    local ret = {}
    for k, v in pairs(tbl) do
      if type(v) == 'table' then
        for _, pair in ipairs(flatten(v)) do
          ret[#ret + 1] = k .. ':' .. pair
        end
      else
        ret[#ret + 1] = k .. '=' .. vim.inspect(v)
      end
    end
    return ret
  end
  vim.list_extend(servers.omnisharp.cmd, flatten(servers.omnisharp.settings))
end

for name, server in pairs(servers) do
  vim.lsp.config(name, server)
  vim.lsp.enable(name)
end
```


I'm using:
neovim 0.11.6
OmniSharp v1.39.15

I only poked around for an hour trying to understand the problem, it's possible that I'm holding it wrong, but that works for me.
